In P&C insurance company, actuaries usually use techniques like Claims reserving with R to estimate claim liabilities. These datasets, unfortunately, didn't organize in the usual format, by calender year or by accident year. So in this notebook, we will use machine learning algorithm to make predictions.

Resolving outliers of the target feature¶

Kernel density estimators (kde) belong to a class of estimators called non-parametric density estimators. In comparison to parametric estimators where the estimator has a fixed functional form (structure) and the parameters of this function are the only information we need to store, Non-parametric estimators have no fixed structure and depend upon all the data points to reach an estimate.

In [12]:

As we can see, it seems there are many outliers in the dataset. They may come from catastrophe loss or significant individual loss, but we have no other information to help us figure it out. So we will just keep them in the future analysis.

Finding the right transformation to resolve Skewness can be tedious. Box and Cox in their 1964 paper proposed a statistical method to find the right transformation. They suggested using below family of transformations and finding the λ:

Box-Cox transform is defined to be x↦(x^λ−1)/λ, as λ→0 this becomes log⁡(x).

In [23]:
for features in cont_features:
    combined[features] = combined[features] + 1
    combined[features], _ = boxcox(combined[features])

Many correlation pairs among categorical features are high. Usually we can use dimensional reduction techniques, like PCA, to select the successive components that explain the maximum variance in the data. Here we will let the machine learning algorithm to learn the pattern of the data.

Feature reduction¶

1. Principal component analysis (PCA)¶

PCA selects the successive components that explain the maximum variance in the signal. The point cloud spanned by the observations is very flat in one direction: one of the three univariate features can almost be exactly computed using the other two. PCA finds the directions in which the data is not flat.

Independent component analysis (ICA) selects components so that the distribution of their loadings carries a maximum amount of independent information. It is able to recover non-Gaussian independent signals.

In [39]:
combined_PCA = combined.copy()

In [41]:
# Set n_components to None to keep all principal components and their explained variance
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import bisect

start_time = time.time()

threshold = 0.99

pca = PCA(whiten=True)
pca.fit(combined_PCA )

varexp = pca.explained_variance_ratio_.cumsum()
cutoff = bisect.bisect(varexp, threshold)

print(cutoff)
print(pca.explained_variance_ratio_.cumsum()[:cutoff+1])

pca = PCA(n_components=cutoff,whiten=True)
pca = pca.fit(combined_PCA)
data_PCA = pca.transform(combined_PCA)

print("predict time:{}s".format(round((time.time()-start_time), 3) ))

3. t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE)¶

t-SNE is a tool to visualize high-dimensional data. It converts similarities between data points to joint probabilities and tries to minimize the Kullback-Leibler divergence between the joint probabilities of the low-dimensional embedding and the high-dimensional data. t-SNE has a cost function that is not convex, i.e. with different initializations we can get different results.

It is highly recommended to use another dimensionality reduction method (e.g. PCA for dense data or TruncatedSVD for sparse data) to reduce the number of dimensions to a reasonable amount (e.g. 50) if the number of features is very high. This will suppress some noise and speed up the computation of pairwise distances between samples.

Machine Learning Algorithm Parameters¶

Algorithm tuning is a final step in the process of applied machine learning before presenting results.

It is sometimes called Hyperparameter optimization where the algorithm parameters are referred to as hyperparameters whereas the coefficients found by the machine learning algorithm itself are referred to as parameters. Optimization suggests the search-nature of the problem.

Phrased as a search problem, you can use different search strategies to find a good and robust parameter or set of parameters for an algorithm on a given problem.

Two simple and easy search strategies are grid search and random search. Scikit-learn provides these two methods for algorithm parameter tuning and examples of each are provided below.

The parameters selected are those that maximize the score of the data, unless an explicit score is passed in which case it is used instead.

Here, we will assume the parameters have already been tuned.

In [46]:
import xgboost as xgb 

start_time = time.time()

xgb_train = xgb.DMatrix(df_train, loss) 
xgb_test = xgb.DMatrix(df_test)

          'objective': 'reg:linear', 
          'max_depth': 6,
          'min_child_weight': 4,
          'subsample': 1, 
          'colsample_bytree': 0.3, 
          'eta': 0.1, 
          'seed':0} 

model = xgb.train(params, xgb_train , num_boost_round = 1001)
predictions_xgb = np.exp(model.predict(xgb_test))

print("predict time:{}s".format(round((time.time()-start_time), 3) ))
